ive in both Marxist and anti-Marxist guises, Weimar Radicals forces us to re-think the fateful relationship between the two great ideological competitors of the Weimar Republic, while offering a challenging new interpretation of the distinctive radicalism of the interwar era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAuthenticity (Philosophy)vCase studies. 0aCommunismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aGroup identityvCase studies. 0aMasculinityxPolitical aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitarismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadicalismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classxPolitical activityzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classzGermanyxPolitical activityxHistoryy20th century. 0aYouth movementszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184545908640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781845459086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781845459086/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK